body:
At the moment there isn't a very good way to retrieve objects from an array indexed by their class string and have Psalm track this relationship.

I'd like to tell Psalm that I have an array of type `array<class-string<Foo>, Foo>` where the class string in the key refers to ***the same*** `Foo` that will be returned. This is roughly equivalent to having a method of the following format as the array-accessor of an array:

```php
/**
 * @template T as Foo
 * @template-typeof T $fooClass
 * @param class-string<T> $fooClass
 * @return T|null
 */
public function get($fooClass);
```

At the moment when I write something like:

```php
interface Foo {}

final class FooStorage
{
    /** @var array<class-string<Foo>, Foo> */
    private $storage = [];
  
    /** @param Foo[] $Foos */
    public function __construct($Foos)
    {
     	foreach ($Foos as $Foo) {
            $this->storage[\get_class($Foo)] = $Foo;
        }
    }
  
    /**
     * @template T as Foo
     * @template-typeof T $fooClass
     * @param class-string<T> $fooClass
     * @return T|null
     */
    public function get($fooClass)
    {
        return $this->storage[$fooClass] ?? null;
    }
}
```

Psalm correctly flags an error since the array accessor on `$this->storage` is only guaranteed to return `Foo` and is not itself generic on the input. If possible, I'd like to tell Psalm that I will assign class strings to map to their objects using some special type (e.g. `class-string-map<T>`) so that something like:

```php
interface Foo {}

final class FooStorage
{
    /** @var class-string-map<Foo> */
    private $storage = [];
  
    /** @param Foo[] $Foos */
    public function __construct($Foos)
    {
     	foreach ($Foos as $Foo) {
            $this->storage[\get_class($Foo)] = $Foo;
        }
    }
  
    /**
     * @template T as Foo
     * @template-typeof T $fooClass
     * @param class-string<T> $fooClass
     * @return T|null
     */
    public function get($fooClass)
    {
        return $this->storage[$fooClass] ?? null;
    }
}
```
would succeed.
